WEBVTT

00:20.098 --> 00:22.540
- So December 3rd, 1999

00:22.540 --> 00:25.510
we went home that night
and about 11:30 at night

00:25.510 --> 00:28.860
we got a call from Hal's
good friend, Jeremy

00:28.860 --> 00:32.887
and he had indicated that Hal
had been in a car accident.

00:33.869 --> 00:36.550
- So the night of Hal's accident,

00:36.550 --> 00:39.710
we were at a conference and
we were coming back from it.

00:39.710 --> 00:41.263
He gets in the car, I get in my car

00:41.263 --> 00:43.160
and we head out.

00:43.160 --> 00:45.373
He got ahead of me and
I caught a red light.

00:48.990 --> 00:51.960
- Hal was driving about 65 miles per hour.

00:51.960 --> 00:54.480
- The drunk driver was
going 80 miles an hour.

00:54.480 --> 00:58.203
- Someone crossed the
median and hit them head on.

01:00.270 --> 01:01.997
His Ford Mustang spun around

01:01.997 --> 01:04.643
and the oncoming driver T-boned him.

01:09.680 --> 01:11.310
- There was like all this debris

01:11.310 --> 01:13.023
in the middle of the freeway.

01:13.023 --> 01:15.737
- And my buddy looks
out the window and says

01:15.737 --> 01:17.470
"I think there was a Mustang
on the side of the road. "

01:17.470 --> 01:19.530
I was like, "Dude, I couldn't even tell. "

01:19.530 --> 01:20.887
And as I kind of started
driving he's like,

01:20.887 --> 01:25.760
"No man, I think that was Hal's Mustang. "

01:25.760 --> 01:27.202
- When I talked to Jeremy,

01:27.202 --> 01:30.210
I told him to tell Hal that we loved him

01:30.210 --> 01:32.680
and that he had to hang in there

01:32.680 --> 01:34.573
and that we were all coming.

01:35.450 --> 01:36.690
- The fire department when they showed up,

01:36.690 --> 01:40.593
they had to cut through the
car to have to pull him out.

01:43.202 --> 01:46.119
(machines beeping)

01:49.140 --> 01:51.790
His heart had stopped for
about six or seven minutes.

01:58.090 --> 02:01.230
- I remember walking through the door

02:01.230 --> 02:03.510
and it was like they'd
been waiting for us.

02:03.510 --> 02:05.370
There was whispers and it
was like the Elrods are here

02:05.370 --> 02:07.383
and then we were rushed into a room.

02:08.380 --> 02:11.800
- The damage that was done
to his body was horrific.

02:11.800 --> 02:15.730
I did not expect him to
live through the weekend.

02:15.730 --> 02:17.080
- He's probably not gonna be able to hear

02:17.080 --> 02:18.270
because of the damage to his ear.

02:18.270 --> 02:19.103
He might not be able to see

02:19.103 --> 02:20.630
'cause he had shattered
bones around his eye.

02:20.630 --> 02:21.790
He'll never walk again.

02:21.790 --> 02:23.840
- There was so much brain trauma

02:23.840 --> 02:26.653
and they told us that
he would be a vegetable.

02:27.790 --> 02:31.073
- I think he was in a
coma for about a week.

02:32.082 --> 02:33.860
- At first, it was like, say goodbye.

02:33.860 --> 02:34.693
Then they were like,

02:34.693 --> 02:37.260
oh, looks like he might make it sort of.

02:37.260 --> 02:39.010
- We knew he was alive inside,

02:39.010 --> 02:40.100
his brain was still working,

02:40.100 --> 02:40.960
he wasn't a vegetable.

02:40.960 --> 02:43.261
And he woke up the next day talking.

02:43.261 --> 02:44.520
- When Hal woke up

02:44.520 --> 02:46.930
his short term memory
was completely impacted.

02:46.930 --> 02:49.043
So it was like Groundhog's Day every day.

02:49.043 --> 02:52.130
I remember one time he's like,
"Did I get in a plane crash?"

02:52.130 --> 02:53.500
I think we went with
that story for the while.

02:53.500 --> 02:57.314
I was like, tomorrow, we'll
retell the real story again.

02:57.314 --> 02:58.800
He took his first step

02:58.800 --> 03:00.610
and it was another one of those things

03:00.610 --> 03:02.110
where people were just shocked

03:02.110 --> 03:04.050
at how fast he was coming back.

03:04.050 --> 03:07.573
- He just defied everything
the doctors said.

03:09.350 --> 03:11.610
We laughed through all of it which is,

03:11.610 --> 03:13.070
you always kind of found humor,

03:13.070 --> 03:15.263
and I think that helped him survive.

03:17.540 --> 03:20.263
- When Hal got out of the
hospital four months later

03:20.263 --> 03:23.607
his high school principal
called and he said,

03:23.607 --> 03:25.437
"I know this is crazy", but he goes,

03:25.437 --> 03:27.700
"do you think Hal would
speak to the student body?"

03:27.700 --> 03:32.223
And so that was the start
really of Hal's speaking career.

03:34.310 --> 03:36.040
- I just feel like Hal
had another purpose,

03:36.040 --> 03:37.240
he wasn't done yet.

03:37.240 --> 03:38.693
I still believe that now.

03:39.680 --> 03:40.603
It was a miracle.

03:53.109 --> 03:56.242
- My mom and dad were
called in by the doctors

03:56.242 --> 03:58.580
after I had been awake for a week

03:58.580 --> 04:01.030
and I had been evaluated
by all the psychologists

04:02.180 --> 04:03.807
and the doctors sat
them down and they said,

04:03.807 --> 04:05.700
"We want to give you an update on Hal. "

04:05.700 --> 04:07.042
They said,

04:07.042 --> 04:09.250
"We're concerned with Hal's
mental and emotional state.

04:09.250 --> 04:13.677
We believe that Hal is
in denial or delusional

04:13.677 --> 04:15.850
because every time we interact with him,

04:15.850 --> 04:19.138
the psychologist, his doctors,
his physical therapist,

04:19.138 --> 04:24.138
Hal's always smiling
and laughing and joking

04:24.180 --> 04:26.580
and telling us jokes, making us laugh. "

04:26.580 --> 04:28.840
And they said, "Frankly,
that's not normal. "

04:28.840 --> 04:31.370
They said, "That's not normal
for a 20 year old young man

04:31.370 --> 04:34.370
that's being told you're
never going to walk again. "

04:34.370 --> 04:37.180
I can't change that I
was in a car accident,

04:37.180 --> 04:38.410
but I can change everything else

04:38.410 --> 04:40.633
and I can damn well choose my attitude.

04:41.720 --> 04:45.160
I will be the happiest,
most grateful person

04:45.160 --> 04:48.493
that you or anyone has
ever seen in a wheelchair.

04:49.520 --> 04:50.623
Consider that.

04:51.550 --> 04:53.023
What's your wheelchair?

04:54.410 --> 04:56.160
What's a circumstance in your life

04:56.160 --> 04:56.993
that you can reference,

04:56.993 --> 04:58.960
past, present, or maybe even

04:58.960 --> 05:00.360
you're worried about for the future

05:00.360 --> 05:02.580
that's out of your control?

05:02.580 --> 05:04.240
Especially if it's in the past, right?

05:04.240 --> 05:06.540
Or if it's happening now
based on past events.

05:07.800 --> 05:08.780
But what's your wheelchair?

05:08.780 --> 05:10.970
What's that experience, that circumstance,

05:10.970 --> 05:12.621
that challenge, that adversity

05:12.621 --> 05:16.126
that has caused you emotional pain

05:16.126 --> 05:20.330
when really you need to take
a deep breath and acknowledge

05:20.330 --> 05:22.903
I can't change it, it's in the past?

05:25.940 --> 05:27.130
I might as well be the happiest,

05:27.130 --> 05:29.503
most grateful person I could ever be

05:29.503 --> 05:32.580
even though that thing happened

05:32.580 --> 05:35.840
or even though I'm going
through that thing right now.

05:35.840 --> 05:37.580
Because see the two
aren't mutually exclusive,

05:37.580 --> 05:39.320
but most of us think that they are.

05:39.320 --> 05:42.767
Most of us think that bad,
painful thing happened,

05:42.767 --> 05:45.623
happening, I feel bad.

05:46.721 --> 05:48.061
Well, the reality is

05:48.061 --> 05:49.150
you can endure

05:49.150 --> 05:51.910
the most difficult painful
circumstance in your life

05:51.910 --> 05:54.280
and choose to be the happiest

05:54.280 --> 05:56.303
and most grateful you've ever been.

05:57.661 --> 06:00.244
(gentle music)

06:01.080 --> 06:03.580
Why is it that when a baby is born,

06:03.580 --> 06:07.002
we often refer to them
as the miracle of life,

06:07.002 --> 06:10.853
but then we go on to accept
mediocrity for our own lives?

06:11.720 --> 06:12.830
Where along the way

06:12.830 --> 06:15.763
did we lose sight of the
miracle that we are living?

06:18.100 --> 06:21.290
Perhaps we became jaded by the challenges,

06:21.290 --> 06:23.543
the setbacks and the disappointments.

06:25.615 --> 06:27.260
When we were born,

06:27.260 --> 06:29.840
everyone assured us that we could do, have

06:29.840 --> 06:32.763
and be anything we wanted when we grew up.

06:34.240 --> 06:36.020
So now that you've grown up,

06:36.020 --> 06:38.640
are you doing, having and being

06:38.640 --> 06:41.363
anything and everything
you've ever wanted?

06:56.301 --> 06:58.384
(crying)

07:05.610 --> 07:07.890
I can only learn, grow

07:07.890 --> 07:10.763
and become better than
I've ever been before.

07:18.609 --> 07:20.420
I think we struggle most in life

07:20.420 --> 07:24.370
when we fail to take
responsibility for our lives.

07:24.370 --> 07:27.820
It's easy to blame other
people, outside forces,

07:27.820 --> 07:30.750
for how we feel or how
we're limited in our life.

07:30.750 --> 07:33.410
But when we allow our outer world

07:33.410 --> 07:34.910
to dictate our inner world,

07:34.910 --> 07:36.000
we give away our power,

07:36.000 --> 07:37.360
we lose control.

07:37.360 --> 07:41.700
And in doing so, we feel
stressed and we get depressed

07:41.700 --> 07:43.990
and we experience fear and anxiety

07:43.990 --> 07:46.740
and life becomes a struggle.

07:46.740 --> 07:49.170
Mentally and emotionally
more prescription medication

07:49.170 --> 07:51.470
is doled out now by doctors

07:51.470 --> 07:53.653
than has ever been recorded in history.

07:54.650 --> 07:58.239
Relationally, the divorce
rate is still over 50%.

07:58.239 --> 08:00.270
Physically, the obesity rate

08:00.270 --> 08:03.199
is higher than it's ever been before.

08:03.199 --> 08:07.520
Financially, there's more
personal debt in the United States

08:07.520 --> 08:10.130
than at any other time in our history.

08:10.130 --> 08:12.220
People are settling for
less than they're capable of

08:12.220 --> 08:15.393
and as a result of settling,
life becomes a struggle.

08:16.450 --> 08:18.940
According to the social
security administration,

08:18.940 --> 08:20.350
if you take any 100 people

08:20.350 --> 08:22.150
at the start of their working careers

08:22.150 --> 08:24.260
and follow them for the next 40 years

08:24.260 --> 08:27.490
until they reach retirement
age, here's what you'll find.

08:27.490 --> 08:29.210
Only one will be wealthy.

08:29.210 --> 08:31.620
Four will be financially secure.

08:31.620 --> 08:33.400
Five will continue working,

08:33.400 --> 08:36.520
not because they want to,
but because they have to.

08:36.520 --> 08:38.120
36 will be dead.

08:38.120 --> 08:40.740
And 54 will be broke and dependent

08:40.740 --> 08:43.530
on friends family, relatives,

08:43.530 --> 08:45.920
and the government to take care of them.

08:45.920 --> 08:47.400
Monetarily speaking,

08:47.400 --> 08:49.800
that's only 5% of us who will succeed

08:49.800 --> 08:51.970
in creating a life of freedom

08:51.970 --> 08:56.170
and 95% who will continue to
struggle their entire lives.

08:56.170 --> 08:58.950
It's no wonder that
nationwide polls have shown

08:58.950 --> 09:02.433
that only one in three
Americans are actually happy.

09:07.830 --> 09:09.310
- Let's talk more about
what's going on here

09:09.310 --> 09:11.420
in this trading session so far today

09:11.420 --> 09:12.610
after this big plunge.

09:12.610 --> 09:15.410
- I've had in my life, what I
would call two rock bottoms.

09:15.410 --> 09:17.640
In 2008, the US economy crashed

09:17.640 --> 09:19.597
and like so many other
people in the world,

09:19.597 --> 09:22.351
I suffered the financial consequences.

09:22.351 --> 09:25.950
Overnight, I lost over half my income,

09:25.950 --> 09:27.570
I couldn't pay my mortgage,

09:27.570 --> 09:29.300
I lost my house,

09:29.300 --> 09:31.170
I was deep in debt,

09:31.170 --> 09:32.810
I got in the worst shape physically,

09:32.810 --> 09:36.159
and for the first time in my
life, I got deeply depressed.

09:36.159 --> 09:38.400
I was a motivational speaker.

09:38.400 --> 09:40.370
To tell everyone that
I was failing miserably

09:40.370 --> 09:42.350
was a real identity crisis for me.

09:42.350 --> 09:43.580
- I was never worried

09:43.580 --> 09:46.540
that Hal was gonna fall into depression

09:46.540 --> 09:48.440
but then he started to,

09:48.440 --> 09:50.320
and I couldn't shake him out of it.

09:50.320 --> 09:54.560
I finally realized that there's
nothing I can do or say.

09:54.560 --> 09:56.060
It needs to be somebody else,

09:56.060 --> 09:58.180
maybe somebody else's
perspective, a third party.

09:58.180 --> 09:59.360
So I recommended that he go

09:59.360 --> 10:01.210
and talk to his friend, Jon Berghoff.

10:03.679 --> 10:04.512
- Hal called me and said,

10:04.512 --> 10:06.320
"JB, I'm really struggling in my life. "

10:06.320 --> 10:08.267
And I just said to him, I said,

10:08.267 --> 10:10.750
"Hey buddy, I don't have all the answers

10:10.750 --> 10:13.070
but I feel like you really need

10:13.070 --> 10:15.017
to become the type of person

10:15.017 --> 10:19.490
that deserves to attract that success. "

10:19.490 --> 10:21.390
And he really took that to heart.

10:21.390 --> 10:23.110
- And I was expecting business advice

10:23.110 --> 10:24.590
you know, step one, step two, step three,

10:24.590 --> 10:26.090
and he said, "Hal, two things,

10:26.090 --> 10:27.400
you need to exercise every morning,

10:27.400 --> 10:29.450
go for a run every morning.

10:29.450 --> 10:30.500
And while you're on that run,

10:30.500 --> 10:32.350
listen to some self-help,

10:32.350 --> 10:34.036
listen to a business audio book. "

10:34.036 --> 10:35.160
And he said, "Put yourself

10:35.160 --> 10:36.980
in a peak, physical,
mental, and emotional state

10:36.980 --> 10:39.310
every morning to start your day

10:39.310 --> 10:41.570
and then learn something
you can apply to your life,

10:41.570 --> 10:43.270
to your business, to your goals

10:43.270 --> 10:44.730
while you're in that peak state. "

10:44.730 --> 10:48.470
And my response was,
"John, I hate running.

10:48.470 --> 10:49.970
What else could I do?"

10:49.970 --> 10:51.207
And without hesitation he said,

10:51.207 --> 10:52.840
"What do you hate worse, running

10:52.840 --> 10:55.830
or your circumstance that
you just described to me?"

10:55.830 --> 10:58.407
I said, "Okay, touche
buddy, I'll go for a run. "

10:59.980 --> 11:01.130
I grabbed my iPod,

11:01.130 --> 11:03.583
which I was this close
to selling for food,

11:03.583 --> 11:07.360
and on that run I heard
a quote from Jim Rohn

11:07.360 --> 11:09.370
that changed my entire life.

11:09.370 --> 11:10.397
Jim Rohn said,

11:10.397 --> 11:11.590
"Your level of success

11:11.590 --> 11:14.320
will seldom exceed your
level of personal development

11:14.320 --> 11:16.356
because success is something you attract

11:16.356 --> 11:17.957
by the person you become. "

11:21.685 --> 11:24.500
I realized I'm not
dedicating time everyday

11:24.500 --> 11:26.030
to my personal development,

11:26.030 --> 11:28.860
therefore I'm not becoming
the person that I need to be

11:28.860 --> 11:31.620
that can attract or create or sustain

11:31.620 --> 11:33.673
the success that I want in my life.

11:37.160 --> 11:38.290
And I had an epiphany.

11:38.290 --> 11:40.790
I thought I'm gonna go home
and I'm gonna go online

11:40.790 --> 11:42.010
and I'm gonna Google,

11:42.010 --> 11:45.230
What are the world's most
successful people do every day

11:45.230 --> 11:46.630
for their personal development?

11:46.630 --> 11:47.961
I'm gonna figure out

11:47.961 --> 11:50.180
what the best personal
development practice is

11:50.180 --> 11:52.950
known to man and I'm gonna do that.

11:52.950 --> 11:54.164
And after an hour of research,

11:54.164 --> 11:55.890
I couldn't narrow it down to one,

11:55.890 --> 11:57.540
I had a list of six.

11:57.540 --> 11:58.622
And those six practices

11:58.622 --> 12:01.720
when I tried to figure out
which was the best of the six,

12:01.720 --> 12:02.810
there was no clear answer,

12:02.810 --> 12:05.640
it depended on which successful
person that you asked.

12:05.640 --> 12:07.740
So I had an epiphany.

12:07.740 --> 12:10.160
I thought, what if I did all six of them?

12:10.160 --> 12:11.420
What if I woke up tomorrow

12:11.420 --> 12:16.000
and I did all six practices
in one hour, one ritual?

12:16.000 --> 12:18.860
My research had shown no one does all six,

12:18.860 --> 12:21.330
maybe one or two, three at the most.

12:21.330 --> 12:22.190
And I thought this would be

12:22.190 --> 12:24.253
the ultimate personal development ritual.

12:29.611 --> 12:31.100
I woke up the next morning,

12:31.100 --> 12:32.302
even though I wasn't a morning person,

12:32.302 --> 12:33.610
I jumped out of bed,

12:33.610 --> 12:34.670
I went into the living room

12:34.670 --> 12:37.998
and I went through all six
practices for 10 minutes each.

12:37.998 --> 12:41.165
(inspirational music)

12:56.190 --> 12:57.510
And at the end of that hour,

12:57.510 --> 13:00.800
by 6:00 a. m. , my entire life changed

13:00.800 --> 13:03.280
because even though my outer
world was still a mess,

13:03.280 --> 13:04.490
even though my finances,

13:04.490 --> 13:06.810
and my physical health my fitness,

13:06.810 --> 13:08.656
everything was a mess on the outside,

13:08.656 --> 13:11.860
internally, I felt like I could overcome

13:11.860 --> 13:13.230
and accomplish anything.

13:13.230 --> 13:14.650
And in that moment I realized

13:14.650 --> 13:17.110
if I start every day like this

13:17.110 --> 13:20.270
with this much clarity
and motivation and energy,

13:20.270 --> 13:21.738
it's only a matter of time

13:21.738 --> 13:24.430
before I become the
person that I need to be,

13:24.430 --> 13:27.943
that can create anything
that I want for my life.

13:33.470 --> 13:35.610
- I remember first hearing
about the Miracle Morning

13:35.610 --> 13:37.760
'cause Hal was doing it

13:37.760 --> 13:41.006
and this was just in casual conversation,

13:41.006 --> 13:43.124
Hal sharing with me

13:43.124 --> 13:46.330
another routine, another
idea, another strategy

13:46.330 --> 13:50.470
that he was using to amplify his life.

13:50.470 --> 13:52.300
When I knew this was something special

13:52.300 --> 13:54.286
is when Hal called me

13:54.286 --> 13:56.910
when I think his name was Joe,

13:56.910 --> 13:59.500
somebody had posted that they
were doing the Miracle Morning

13:59.500 --> 14:01.450
and they had posted a
picture of their alarm clock

14:01.450 --> 14:06.050
and I remember the first
time that he saw the impact

14:06.050 --> 14:11.050
and the feeling that I
remember is the joy of Hal

14:12.440 --> 14:14.893
knowing that he was
helping another person.

14:16.062 --> 14:17.065
- Good morning.

14:17.065 --> 14:19.180
This is your friend, Joe, Joe De Sena,

14:19.180 --> 14:20.870
hope you're doing well.

14:20.870 --> 14:21.760
Guess what?

14:21.760 --> 14:22.910
Let's look at the time.

14:24.160 --> 14:29.097
It is 5:41 in the morning on Sunday.

14:31.500 --> 14:33.810
You must be wondering
what in the world dude

14:33.810 --> 14:35.801
are you doing this early in the morning?

14:35.801 --> 14:39.750
Well, check out Miracle Morning.

14:39.750 --> 14:41.580
It feels like Christmas to me, honestly

14:41.580 --> 14:42.937
and I've got a lot of energy.

14:42.937 --> 14:44.330
It's like Christmas every day.

14:44.330 --> 14:46.500
So anyways, check it out

14:46.500 --> 14:48.150
and hope your life will be blessed,

14:48.150 --> 14:49.273
I'll talk to you soon.

14:51.070 --> 14:53.650
- I didn't see how viral it would become

14:53.650 --> 14:55.860
where when somebody would
implement this into their life

14:55.860 --> 14:58.790
that they would then tell
other people as well.

14:58.790 --> 15:00.998
- So I actually got up at 5:00 a. m..

15:00.998 --> 15:02.360
- Good morning.

15:02.360 --> 15:04.360
It's just after six o'clock.

15:04.360 --> 15:06.220
- How to have a Miracle Morning

15:06.220 --> 15:08.300
coming to you from Jaco, Costa Rica.

15:08.300 --> 15:10.750
- I came out to work
out only in the morning,

15:10.750 --> 15:12.558
little bit earlier than my usual time.

15:12.558 --> 15:16.958
- (speaking in foreign
language) Miracle Morning.

15:16.958 --> 15:17.840
- I am not a morning person

15:17.840 --> 15:19.570
but anyone can do the Miracle Morning

15:19.570 --> 15:21.413
because it's customized to you.

15:22.260 --> 15:24.441
- You getting your Miracle Morning on?

15:24.441 --> 15:26.350
(baby cooing)

15:26.350 --> 15:28.010
- Yeah?

15:28.010 --> 15:30.303
Do you know what silence is?

